 for bestpractices and # Dashboard

## Overview
This prompt guides an AI development tool to build the LifeOps Personal Dashboard. The dashboard serves as the primary user workspace, presenting at-a-glance status and actionable insights across Projects, Content drafts & scheduling, Financial snapshot, Health summary, and recent AI actions with an explainable audit trail. It integrates an AI Assistant with explainability, an Agent Orchestration Layer for modular AI agents, and an Onboarding/Permissions Setup flow. All code must defensively guard against null/undefined values, use proper runtime safety patterns, and align with the provided design system and branding.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Dashboard is the central workspace for individual users to manage their life-operations across multiple domains (Projects, Content, Finance, Health) with a focus on clarity, explainability, and auditable AI actions.

Goals:
- Provide a cohesive, single view of key metrics and activities.
- Enable quick actions via module shortcuts and contextual actions.
- Surface explainable AI decisions with sources, rationale, and confidence levels.
- Log and present an audit trail of recent AI actions with per-action explainability and undo/rollback where applicable.
- Allow seamless navigation to onboarding/permissions setup for connecting modules, preferences, and agent permissions.

Connected features:
- AI Assistant & Explainability: ideation, writing, planning, forecasting, and recommendations with sources, rationale, and confidence levels.
- Agent Orchestration Layer: modular AI agents coordinating tasks with permission checks, explainability, and audit logs.

UI elements & visual guidance:
- Top Summary Cards: quick metrics (active projects, upcoming content, net monthly cashflow, today’s wellness metric)
- Recent Activity Feed: shows agent actions, published content, flagged transactions, completed workouts
- Module Shortcuts: quick-create actions for Project, Content, Budget, Workout
- Explainability Panel: displays recent AI decisions with Why/Undo options
- Global Search Bar: cross-module search across projects, content, transactions, and health logs
- Sidebar Navigation: module sections, settings, notifications
- Visuals adhere to the provided color palette, typography, grid system, and card-based layout with mobile-first responsiveness and bottom navigation on mobile.

Visual style and branding:
- Use the provided color palette, typography, and layout guidelines.
- Emphasize a premium, professional, and trustworthy Life OS aesthetic with warm yellow accents (primary actions) and neutral grays.
- Ensure accessible contrast ratios, responsive typography, and scalable UI.

API integration status:
- No external APIs are connected for this task (internal data sources only). All data fetching should be prepared to handle null/undefined results gracefully (see runtime safety section).

## Components to Build
- DashboardShell: the overall page container with header, sidebar, bottom navigation (mobile), and content grid.
- SummaryCard: reusable card component for metrics with an icon/thumbnail, title, value, and optional trend data.
- ProjectsPanel: shows active projects, progress, upcoming milestones.
- ContentPanel: displays content drafts, schedules, publish timeline.
- FinancePanel: shows net cashflow, expenses, forecasted spending.
- HealthPanel: wellness metrics, training plans, dietary suggestions.
- AIExplainabilityPanel: a panel listing recent AI decisions with Why, Confidence, Sources, and Undo action.
- ActivityFeed: real-time-like feed showing agent actions, content publications, transactions flagged, workouts completed.
- AIShortcutPanel: module shortcuts (Create Project, Create Content, Create Budget, Create Workout).
- GlobalSearchBar: searchable input with results across modules.
- OnboardingModal/Screen (connected page): guided onboarding for module connections, preferences, and agent permissions.
- PermissionManagerPanel (onboarding): per-module and per-agent permission toggles and audit trail pointers.
- ChartContainer: lightweight data visualization components (bar/line charts) for finance and health metrics.
- AuditTrailList: detailed, filterable view of agent actions with explainability metadata.

Technical details for components:
- All components should be written in a modern React + TypeScript stack (or your preferred framework with equivalent capabilities).
- Use a state management approach appropriate for the project (e.g., React context, Redux Toolkit, Zustand) to share data across the dashboard and explainability panel.
- Ensure all array accesses are null-safe; default to empty arrays with data ?? [] guards where applicable.
- All visual components must be accessible (ARIA attributes, semantic HTML where possible).

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Routing: Dashboard as the main route; Onboarding/Permissions Setup as a protected route, accessible via a dedicated path.
- UI Components:
  - Button variants: Primary (solid #FFD400), Secondary (outlined/ghost with borders), and Icon buttons.
  - Inputs: Rounded 12–14px radii; borders #E5E7EB; focus ring #FDE047 or #FFD400.
  - Cards: White with soft shadows, 1px border (#E6E8EC), 12–16px border radius, internal typography and data rows.
  - Layout: Mobile-first single-column cards; on larger viewports, 2–3 column cards with balanced white space.
  - Navigation: Fixed bottom nav on mobile with evenly spaced icons; central FAB in #FFD400 with shadow.
- Data Handling:
  - Mock data sources or API stubs for Projects, Content, Finance, Health, and AI actions, returning possibly null data to validate runtime safety.
  - Defensive data rendering: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - Global search should filter across available datasets with safe checks.
- Explainability:
  - Explainability panel shows a list of explainable AI decisions with source links, rationale, and confidence scores.
  - Each explainable item should include a Why section and an Undo action where appropriate (undo should trigger a simulated revert with confirmation).
- Accessibility:
  - All interactive elements accessible via keyboard.
  - Proper semantic headings, alt text for icons, and readable contrast ratios.
- Performance:
  - Debounced global search.
  - Memoized components where appropriate (React.memo) to avoid unnecessary re-renders.

### Backend
- No external APIs required for this task. Prepare placeholders or mock endpoints if needed for local development.
- Data models to support frontend:
  - Projects: id, title, status, progress, dueDate, notes
  - ContentDrafts: id, title, status, scheduleDate, preview
  - Finance: id, month, netCashflow, forecast, expenses
  - Health: id, metricName, value, unit, timestamp
  - AIActionAudit: id, actionType, timestamp, actor, rationale, sources, confidence
- API response patterns:
  - Ensure response shapes are validated: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Whenever returning lists from endpoints, wrap with nullish coalescing: data ?? [].
- Security:
  - JWT-based authentication skeleton (mock) with authorization guards for sensitive endpoints (e.g., Undo action, permissions changes).
  - Role-based access (user vs admin) implied in the design with placeholders.
- Validation:
  - Input validations for onboarding (permissions, preferences), using robust validation rules (e.g., allowed lists, required fields).

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - Dashboard components fetch data from consolidated API layer. All data retrieval should guard against null with data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks.
  - AIExplainabilityPanel consumes explainability data, with sources, rationale, confidence, and optionally undo actions.
  - Onboarding flow writes permission settings and module connections to a local store or mock API; changes reflect in Agent Orchestration Layer mock state.
- State synchronization:
  - Use a single source of truth for UI state (selected module, search query, filter states) with proper defaults.
  - Derived metrics (e.g., upcoming content count, net cashflow) should be computed from arrays with safe guards: const upcomingContent = (contentDrafts ?? []).filter(...).length.

## User Experience Flow
- Step 1: User lands on Dashboard; summary cards load (Projects, Content, Finance, Health) with quick glance metrics.
- Step 2: User scans Activity Feed for AI actions and recent publications; can click an action to view explainability details.
- Step 3: User uses Global Search to locate a project, content draft, or health log; results show with safe rendering.
- Step 4: User clicks Module Shortcuts to create a new Project/Content/Budget/Workout; forms appear in a modal or panel with validated input.
- Step 5: User opens Explainability Panel to review recent AI decisions; uses Why to understand reasoning and Undo to revert actions (where allowed).
- Step 6: User opens Onboarding/Permissions Setup to connect modules and set agent permissions; applies preferences and grants permissions to agents/integrations.
- Step 7: Data changes trigger audit logs and update the Agent Orchestration Layer state, visible in the Audit Trail.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models (Schema Highlights):
- Projects: { id: string, title: string, status: 'planning' | 'in-progress' | 'done', progress: number, dueDate?: string, notes?: string[] }
- ContentDrafts: { id: string, title: string, status: 'draft' | 'scheduled' | 'published', scheduleDate?: string, preview?: string }
- Finance: { id: string, month: string, netCashflow: number, forecast: number, expenses: number }
- Health: { id: string, metricName: string, value: number, unit: string, timestamp: string }
- AIActionAudit: { id: string, actionType: string, timestamp: string, actor: string, rationale: string, sources: string[], confidence: number }

API Endpoints (Routes and Methods):
- GET /api/dashboard/summary -> { projects: Project[], contentDrafts: ContentDraft[], finance: Finance[], health: Health[], aiAudits: AIActionAudit[] }
- GET /api/dashboard/ai-explain/:actionId -> { actionId, explanation: string, sources: string[], rationale: string, confidence: number }
- POST /api/dashboard/ai-action/undo -> { success: boolean, actionId: string }
- GET /api/dashboard/search?q=... -> { results: { type: 'project'|'content'|'finance'|'health', item: any }[] }
- POST /api/onboarding/connect-module -> { success: boolean, module: string, config: any }
- POST /api/onboarding/permissions -> { success: boolean, permissions: Record<string, boolean> }

Security:
- Authentication: Mock JWT validation; ensure endpoints require a valid token for access.
- Authorization: Actions that mutate state (Undo, onboarding, permission changes) require a valid role with permission to modify that resource.
- Data validation: All inputs validated server-side (even in mock endpoints) to prevent invalid state.

Validation:
- Client-side and server-side validations for all forms (e.g., onboarding form step completion, permission toggles).
- Ensure all array operations guard for nulls: use (array ?? []) or Array.isArray(array) ? array.map(...) : [].
- Use default states for arrays: useState<Type[]>([]) and initialize data structures accordingly.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Dashboard renders with 4 primary KPI cards and 1-2 charts that adapt to mobile/desktop breakpoints.
- [ ] All dataset renderings guard against null/undefined values; use (data ?? []) and Array.isArray checks in all rendering logic.
- [ ] AI Explainability panel shows at least 3 recent AI decisions with sources, rationale, and confidence; Undo action triggers a simulated revert with user confirmation.
- [ ] Global search returns results across Projects, Content, Finance, and Health with safe rendering and debounced input.
- [ ] Onboarding/Permissions Setup page exists and allows connecting at least two modules, setting preferences, and granting agent permissions; all state changes reflect in the audit log or agent state.
- [ ] All forms validate input; errors are user-friendly, and focus states are accessible.
- [ ] Data models and API mocks align with the defined schemas; all API responses validate shapes before rendering.

UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Implement the design as described in Visual Style, Typography & Layout, and Key Design Elements.
- Ensure mobile-first approach with bottom navigation, FAB, and collapsible side panels on larger devices.
- Use the specified color palette, gradients, typography, spacings, and card styling consistently across all components.
- Maintain consistent micro-interactions (hover glows, tap ripples, transitions 200–250ms) for a premium experience.
- Ensure charts use a restrained color palette with yellow accents, light gridlines, and accessible labels.

Visual Style (Referenced)
- Primary Accent: #FFD400
- Secondary Accent: #FFEA00
- Surface / UI White: #FFFFFF
- Background: #F2F4F7
